        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Sensitivity: We have a detection of 0.4 mJy beam^{-1} with GISMO 2mm at the position of the galaxy. Want to confirm the association of that detection with the galaxy MACS1149-JD at z=9.6. By looking to the spectral energy distribution for MACS1149-JD assuming the association of the GISMO detection, we should have a brighter or at least equal continuum level at 1.3 mm. Because we need a high significance detection to constrain the SED, we request to get a 15 sigma detection with an rms of  0.025 mJy beam^{-1}.

Bandwidth for sensitivity: We use the aggregate bandwidth of 7.4 GHz to estimate the continuum rms. This is a continuum project. For the SPWs in FDM mode, we request a channel averaging with N=16.

Representative frequency: We used the SPW at the highest frequency as the representative frequency. The SPWs at the lower frequency should have a better atmosphere transmission than the representative frequency, securing the sensitivity requested.

Angular Resolution and Largest Angular structure: The measured size of the galaxy is 0.6", smaller than the ALMA beam at 230 GHz. We still request the compact configuration with a resolution of 1.6" because of the possibility of that the dust emission is more extended than the optical size. We want to maximize the efficiency of the observations. This angular resolution is more than enough to confirm the association of the 2 mm and 1.3 mm emission with MACS1149-JD.

Total bandwidth: This is a continuum project, we request for the total bandwidth of 7.4 GHz.

Line: We expect the line to have a peak of ~4 mJy. We reach an rms of 0.8 mJy beam^{-1} for a channel resolution of 10 km s^-1, enough to have a 5 sigma detection. If the redshift is close to z=9.6, we should be able to detect and resolve the line. We want to make clear that the search for the [NII] 122 microns emission line is a secondary objective. The sensitivity obtained for the line search is a consequence of the time requested to detect the continuum. </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
