    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>We propose to use ALMA to follow-up on the exciting GISMO 2 mm detection of a source located within 8" of the galaxy MACS J1149+2223 that was detected with Hubble and Spitzer. Its detection was enabled by the presence of a foreground cluster with a gravitational magnification of about 15. The photometric redshift of this galaxy is 9.6, providing astronomers with the rare opportunity to observe the very early phases of galaxy evolution, when the universe was about 500 Myr old. Confirming MACS1149-JD as the millimeter GISMO source will render it  the youngest dust-forming galaxy detected so far, with profound implication for the cosmic star formation rate, the rate of metal enrichment, and the origin, nature, and evolution of dust in the very early universe. The prime objective of the proposal is to observe MACS1149-JD in the 232 GHz band (1.3 mm), confirming the GISMO association by adding a high-angular resolution millimeter observation of the dust continuum emission, and possibly determining  the spectroscopic redshift of this galaxy using the [NII] 122 microns fine-structure line.</prp:abstract>
